			<h3>XNA Game <span class="alt">Glasshouse</span></h3>
			
			Along with a team of my classmates I created the XNA based game <span class="alt">Glasshouse</span>.
			
			<br><br>
			
			It has the following standard features:
			
			<br><br>
			
			<ul>
				<li>Written in C# using the <a href="http://creators.xna.com/en-US/">XNA</a> framework</li>
				<li>All custom shaders using <a href="http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb509561%28VS.85%29.aspx">HLSL</a>. Some of
				the shaders include:
					<ul>
						<li>Bloom</li>
						<li>Seperable Blur (two passes)</li>
						<li>Glow</li>
						<li>Multi-pass Refraction</a>
					</ul>
				</li>
				<li>All surfaces use fully dynamic lighting (unified lighting system, nearest N lights active at a time)</li>
				<li>Percentage closer filtered shadow maps</li>
				<li>Normal mapping in all surface shaders</li>
				<li>18 levels of gameplay (about 2 hours to complete on average)</li>
				<li>Physics system integration (<a href="http://jiglibx.codeplex.com/">JigLibX</a> physics engine)</li>
			</ul>
			
		</div>

